node.text: Short film by @taylorglenn | We all know people whose dedication to a passion or purpose inspires us deeply. Gannett Horn's (@surfasaur) focus on his sport and love for its community embodies the best in each of us. This short film is a testament to Gannett and those who motivate us to work harder at the things we love. #riversurfing Production by @apresvisuals

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Adventure on July 29, 2021. May be an image of ski slope, snow and nature.

node.text: Photo by @ming.t.poon / @codytownsend skiing through the inversion layer near his home in Lake Tahoe. We had been shut down by an inversion; it seemed as if we were in a Ping-Pong ball. Right around sunset, the sun reflected off the clouds above and into this inversion layer, creating a pink hue. It was incredible, perfectly diffused light. We scrambled to get a few shots, including this one, then the light was gone within 5 minutes. Get it while you can!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Adventure on July 29, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: Photo by @jason_gulley_science / Glaciologist Celia Trunz downloads data from a research GPS station on the Greenland ice sheet in October 2017. The station records its position every few seconds as it is dragged toward the ocean with the ice sheet, providing scientists with a high resolution record of ice sheet motion. GPS stations like this one show that as rising temperatures eat away at marine-terminating glaciers and cause them to retreat, inland ice is speeding up. This faster-moving ice dumps icebergs into the ocean—and contributes to sea level rise—more quickly than a few decades ago. #Greenland #Arctic #climate #climatechange #sealevel

node.text: Photos by @donaldmiralle / Day 5 at the Tokyo Olympics: whitewater action at women’s kayak finals. As with most of the Olympic sports, I shoot canoeing and kayaking every four years but wish I could shoot them more often. The slalom facility is an artificial course with challenging gates for athletes to maneuver and photographers to shoot!

node.text: Photo by @donaldmiralle / Synchronized 10M Diving is a crazy @olympics sport where the athletes throw themselves off a platform the height of a three story building while spinning and flipping around. Here are Yuan Cao and Aisen Chen of China spinning in unison from dizzying heights. China ended up with the silver medal behind Great Britain’s Thomas Daley and Marty Lee.

node.text:
Photos by @donaldmiralle / Day 4 at the Tokyo @olympics started off with a bang and one of my favorite sports to cover, the triathlon. You have to love a good triathlon, where you get 3 sports in 1 and the athletes push themselves to the absolute limits.

The men gave it their all and it made for an exciting race with @kristianblu hammered it down the stretch and captured the 🥇 for 🇳🇴.
